                    <!-- Detailed Sections -->
                    <div class="space-y-8">
                        <!-- Economy & Landmarks -->
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="flex items-center text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">
                                <i data-lucide="landmark" class="h-6 w-6 mr-3 text-blue-600"></i>
                                Economy & Landmarks
                            </h3>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
                                Manila's economy is diverse, with major activities in finance, commerce, tourism, and shipping, thanks to the Port of Manila, the largest in the country. The city is home to numerous historical and cultural landmarks.
                            </p>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside mt-4 space-y-1 text-gray-700">
                                <li><strong>Intramuros:</strong> The historic walled city containing Fort Santiago and San Agustin Church.</li>
                                <li><strong>Rizal Park:</strong> A large urban park dedicated to the national hero, José Rizal.</li>
                                <li><strong>National Museum Complex:</strong> Comprising museums of Fine Arts, Anthropology, and Natural History.</li>
                                <li><strong>Binondo:</strong> The world's oldest Chinatown, a hub of commerce and cuisine.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        
                        <!-- History -->
                        <div>
                             <h3 class="flex items-center text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">
                                <i data-lucide="scroll-text" class="h-6 w-6 mr-3 text-blue-600"></i>
                                History
                            </h3>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
                                Before Spanish colonization, Manila was the seat of the Kingdom of Maynila, a major trading partner with Asian nations. In 1571, Spanish conquistador Miguel López de Legazpi founded the modern city. It became the capital of the Spanish East Indies for centuries. The city was heavily devastated during the Battle of Manila in World War II but has since been rebuilt and has continued to grow.
                            </p>
                        </div>

                        <!-- Geography & Climate -->
                        <div>
                             <h3 class="flex items-center text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">
                                <i data-lucide="mountain-snow" class="h-6 w-6 mr-3 text-blue-600"></i>
                                Geography & Climate
                            </h3>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
                                Manila is located on the eastern shores of Manila Bay. The Pasig River flows through the middle of the city, dividing it into north and south sections. Like the rest of the Philippines, Manila has a tropical climate characterized by a wet and a dry season.
                            </p>
                        </div>
